            <yt-formatted-string id="published-time-text" class="style-scope ytd-comment-renderer" has-link-only_=""><a class="yt-simple-endpoint style-scope yt-formatted-string" spellcheck="false" href="/watch?v=4INdeZ5HYpw&amp;lc=UgwC6-ugrTRwn76RM9F4AaABAg">3 days ago</a></yt-formatted-string>

    <div id="content" class="style-scope ytd-expander">

      <yt-formatted-string id="voted-option" slot="content" class="style-scope ytd-comment-renderer" disable-upgrade="" hidden="">
          </yt-formatted-string><yt-formatted-string id="content-text" slot="content" split-lines="" class="style-scope ytd-comment-renderer">Having a very general impression of organic chemistry (carbon backbones, reactive groups, a few more things) is fine. Otherwise, ONLY ORGANIC CHEMISTS need to know organic chemistry. I went to med school and I have a PhD in cell biology. I never needed any organic chemistry for ANY of that (despite EVERYONE insisting it is vital). Anyone who says different is a LIAR! Furthermore, if you consider carefully and without bias, you will see that this brief lecture is actually DEVOID of any useful or meaningful information (for anyone who has enough basic chemistry to understand what atoms and molecules are, and enough biology to have some idea about what cells do, and how their processes are mediated through macromolecules made up of the well known building blocks of all biological materials). Yeah, epinephrine has a structure (which doesn't MATTER -- as long as you understand the general principle that all enzymes and other binding sites in biology rest on structures fitting together electro-mechanically) -- so what? It matters to anyone synthesizing epinephrine (organic chemists), and it matters to someone working on the biochemistry of epinephrine (i.e., organic chemists who work on biological systems).&#65279;</yt-formatted-string>
    </div>

Michel Legrand's achievement as song composer and finest living  arranger orchestrator is  without equal among contemporaries. Legrand's songs  are occasionally informed by a contemporary pop sensibility -- Breezy -- On my way to you -- Something new in my life. Others are moodily substantial e.g. Between yesterday and tomorrow. There's the whimsical conceit of Maybe someone dreamed us enveloping a winsome melody. But these are just jottings on  an illustrious six decade career that began as Sinatra was moving into top gear in the early 50's  rubbing  shoulders with  greats of the music industry winning respect of his peers. Jazz saxophonist Stan Getz commented favourably on Legrand's completeness as musician. A favourite aspect of Legrand's artistry is his long-standing brilliance as a jazz pianist. I especially delight in his soloistic piano contributions to his orchestral albums, too many tracks to mention but Make Me Rainbows already up on YouTube is always worth a listen. His Cole Porter album 1957  with classically \"sheened\" finish runs the gamut in orchestral brilliance and for my money is streets ahead of any popular orchestral album from the era  Legrands  musical   qualities   among among other   aspects  ~ virtuosity    are French in feel but the    effect  is universal. Michel Legrand's achievement as song composer and finest living  arranger orchestrator is  without equal among contemporaries. Legrand's songs  are occasionally informed by a contemporary pop sensibility -- Breezy -- On my way to you -- Something new in my life. Others are moodily substantial e.g. Between yesterday and tomorrow. There's the whimsical conceit of Maybe someone dreamed us enveloping a winsome melody. But these are just jottings on  an illustrious six decade career that began as Sinatra was moving into top gear in the early 50's  rubbing  shoulders with  greats of the music industry winning respect of his peers. Jazz saxophonist Stan Getz commented favourably on Legrand's completeness as musician. A favourite aspect of Legrand's artistry is his long-standing brilliance as a jazz pianist. I especially delight in his soloistic piano contributions to his orchestral albums, too many tracks to mention but Make Me Rainbows already up on YouTube is always worth a listen. His Cole Porter album 1957  with classically \"sheened\" finish runs the gamut in orchestral brilliance and for my money is streets ahead of any popular orchestral album from the era  Legrands  musical   qualities   among among other   aspects  ~ virtuosity    are French in feel but the    effect  is universal.  With a handful of  finest  mid 20th century musicians  Legrands music   transcends
